A pair of Grey Wagtails was searching along a fast-flowing burn (small stream) near the village of Crawfordsburn. The male, over the course of an hour, gathered nest material and seemed to deposit it inside a cavity in an old stone wall. Despite his endeavours, the female was unimpressed and moved downstream (towards my location) and appeared to make nest site investigations by herself. The male accompanied her. At times one or other bird was  watched foraging for insects that were usually so small as to be invisible to me. The recording was made when the male was in view. I suspect the female was close by but I had a very limited view from a hide. At one point in the recording (at 0:17) it seems as though a double-note uttered by the male is answered immediately by the female (unless the male repeated his double note in quick succession). The double note is, of course, also the typical flight call. Examples are at 0:02, 0:03, 0:05. Often the same 'couplet' actually has three syllables, not two. Examples of triple utterances are 0:08, 0:24 and 0:34. Based on the male's calls, a single syllable is also used, possibly influenced by the presence of a partner. There are several single notes among the recording and perhaps some were made by the female. In any event, I could see the male over most of the recording and I'm confident that, for instance, the single note at 0:21 was given by him. Even though the species song phrase (0:28 and 0:36) also has three syllables (some songsters employ up to five syllables, thereby creating more of a trill) these are different and have a different pitch. They are somewhat reminiscent of a phrase delivered by Blue Tit.
